  "runtimeMin": 146,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey runs a Studio Ghibli roundtable with Andy Greenwald, Charles Holmes, and producer Bobby Wagoner on Hayao Miyazaki's 'The Boy and the Heron' and everyone's top-five Miyazaki. Then he and Amanda Dobbins spoil their way through Justine Triet's 'Anatomy of a Fall.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'The Boy and the Heron'",
      "note": "Miyazaki's first film in a decade",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Boy and the Heron",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Miyazaki's first feature since 2013, six years in the making and the most expensive Japanese film ever. Its Japanese title, 'How Do You Live,' nods to the 1937 novel. A wartime boy, Mahito, follows a talking heron into a fantastical world after losing his mother; the panel reads it as Miyazaki's most personal and confounding work, his 'Irishman.' Christian Bale voices the father in the dub, Robert Pattinson the heron. Opened No. 1 at the U.S. box office."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Top Five Miyazaki Movies",
      "note": "ranked by rough consensus of four ballots",
      "subject": "Hayao Miyazaki",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Spirited Away",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "Unanimous No. 1 for all four. Called the 'Wizard of Oz of Japanese animation,' the text everyone else gets measured against."
        },
        {
          "title": "My Neighbor Totoro",
          "year": 1988,
          "note": "No. 2 for Charles, Andy, and Sean. Charles says it hit hardest on a pandemic rewatch, when the sick-mother undercurrent came through."
        },
        {
          "title": "Princess Mononoke",
          "year": 1997,
          "note": "On every ballot. Bobby's No. 2 and his 'morally complex' pick, which he likens to 'Avatar.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ponyo",
          "year": 2008,
          "note": "Charles's No. 4, and part of Andy's and Bobby's ties. The safe-and-warm mode of Miyazaki."
        },
        {
          "title": "Kiki's Delivery Service",
          "year": 1989,
          "note": "Sean's No. 5, Andy's No. 3. Kirsten Dunst voices Kiki and Phil Hartman the cat in the dub."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Wind Rises",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "Sean's No. 3, Andy's No. 4. Miyazaki's 2013 'retirement' film, a projected biopic of the man who designed the A6M Zero."
        },
        {
          "title": "Howl's Moving Castle",
          "year": 2004,
          "note": "Bobby's No. 5. A big popular hit in America, though the others admit they aren't Howl's people."
        },
        {
          "title": "Porco Rosso",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "Charles's No. 3. Miyazaki's self-described 'failure': a fascist-era ace cursed with a pig's head."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "An 'Anatomy of a Fall' Deep Dive",
      "note": "full spoilers, with Amanda Dobbins",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Anatomy of a Fall",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Justine Triet's Palme d'Or winner, Sandra Hüller as a writer tried for her husband's fall from their French Alps home. A full-spoilers dive on the marriage, the French courtroom, and the son's decisive testimony, ending on the unanswered did-she-do-it. Touchstones: the 50 Cent 'P.I.M.P.' instrumental, Milo Machado-Graner as Daniel, and Snoop the dog, that year's Palm Dog winner."
        }
      ]
    }
